"This document is a project report by Group 11 of the Computer Science department at the Indian Institute of Information Technology Vadodara for the academic year 2025-2026, detailing the development of the ChatSphere real-time chat application. The project was guided by Dr. Pooja Mishra and assisted by Tejas Kalal.\n\nChatSphere is a modern, user-friendly, and scalable real-time web application designed to enhance communication efficiency by separating professional and casual conversations into distinct \"Work Mode\" and \"Private Mode.\" The application begins with a landing page offering user registration and login. During registration, users provide personal details and a security question for password recovery. Upon login, users select their desired mode, which directs them to a chat interface.\n\nThe chat interface is rich in features, supporting direct messaging, group chats, starred messages, message categorization, file storage, and real-time message editing. It also includes robust search functionality and theme switching between dark and light modes, aiming to improve usability and organization over existing systems. The report highlights several problems with current applications, including the lack of separation between professional and personal chats, difficulties in managing messages and files, limited search capabilities, and poor customization options.\n\nThe project's objectives were to create a secure and user-friendly application that enables chat separation, organizes messages and files, supports real-time communication, and offers efficient search. The report outlines the detailed requirements, encompassing functional requirements (user registration, login, password recovery, mode selection, direct messaging, group chats, starring messages, file categorization, real-time editing, search, profile settings, theme switching) and non-functional requirements (security, performance, usability, scalability, reliability).\n\nThe technical foundation of ChatSphere includes a client-server architecture with a React (Vite) frontend, Flask backend, and SQLite database, utilizing Cloudinary for file storage. The document details the system architecture, use case diagrams, data flow, and database design, which includes tables for users, messages, rooms, starred messages, categories, and files.\n\nThe implementation details cover various modules, starting from the landing page and user registration, through login, forgot password functionality, mode selection, and the core chat features. Specific modules addressed include direct chat, room management, starred messages, file storage, search, user settings, and theme switching. The report also details the \"Mode Switching Module\" for flexibility.\n\nTesting was a crucial part of the development process, employing a strategy that included Unit, Integration, Functional, and UI testing. Various test cases were outlined and executed for registration, login, password recovery, mode selection, chat functionalities, message editing, room management, and file operations. The report confirms that all outlined test cases passed, indicating the successful implementation of the core features.\n\nIn conclusion, ChatSphere has successfully delivered a real-time chat application that effectively separates conversations into Work and Private modes. It offers enhanced organization through features like message categorization, starred messages, and file management, improving upon the limitations of existing messaging platforms. The project report also proposes future enhancements such as voice/video calling, end-to-end encryption, push notifications, message reactions, AI suggestions, and an admin dashboard."